# Reflection

## Activity Description

For my Career Development Experience, I selected my IT Security Infrastructure internship at L3Harris Technologies where I got the chance to work on improving enterprise security operations infrastructure. The goal of this internship at the time was to gain hands-on cybersecurity experience and contribute meaningful improvements while also developing my professional skills.

My work mainly focused on supporting SOC platforms, improving security documentation governance, optimizing log ingestion workflows, and troubleshooting security integrations.

## Technical and Professional Decisions

One important decision I made was to focus on understanding the operational impact of technical work rather than just completing tasks. Since I wasn’t necessarily always simply assigned tasks, I tried to understand how improvements affected efficiency, and security outcomes. Another decision was learning how to communicate clearly with experienced engineers and security professionals. During my time as an Intern, I worked with people from different security teams in order to get certain projects done, and this really developed my ability to work in a team of this scale.

## Contributions

I worked both independently and with the threat mitigation team where I completed troubleshooting and documentation tasks independently while supporting larger engineering projects.

My individual contributions included supporting SIEM ingestion optimization, improving SOP documentation, assisting security platform troubleshooting, and supporting endpoint policy improvements.

## Quality Assessment

I believe I performed well because I focused on learning quickly, asking questions, and trying to understand the larger security environment. I also tried to identify areas where I could contribute beyond assigned tasks, as that seemed to be vital in how I received a return offer.

If I could improve anything, I would track my work more systematically throughout the internship so I could better quantify progress and improvements. I did have information I mentioned on my resume, but many metrics are missing because of my lack of proper tracking of them.

## Career Alignment

This experience strongly supported my career goals by giving me real exposure to enterprise security engineering environments, and it confirmed my interest in cybersecurity, as well as deepening my interest in the infrastructure engineering side of things and preparing me for full-time work when I return. Receiving a return offer as an Information Security Systems Engineer demonstrated that I am progressing toward my goal of becoming a security engineer, and this experience significantly strengthened my technical confidence and clarified my career direction.
